-- Sub-Saharan African Stocks: Air Mauritius, Honeywell Flour, Kenya Airways
-- Eric Ombok
-- 2010-06-23T17:09:47Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-23/sub-saharan-african-stocks-air-mauritius-honeywell-flour-kenya-airways.html

          
          
             The  Nigerian Stock Exchange All-
Share Index  dropped for a fourth day, retreating 0.8 percent to
25,554.35 at the close in Lagos.  
 Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  closed 0.2 percent higher at
1,644.60, while Kenya’s  All-Share Index  rose for the first day
in three, adding 0.4 percent to 73.57 at the close in Nairobi.
Namibia’s  FTSE/Namibia Overall Index  fell 0.8 percent to 767.85,
while the  Ghana Stock Exchange All-Share Index  decreased for a
second day, falling 0.3 percent to 6,690.8.  
 The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  
 Air Mauritius Ltd.  (AML MP), the state-owned carrier, fell
the most in seven trading days, dropping 0.3 rupees, or 2.1
percent, to 14.2 rupees. Mauritian Finance Minister  Pravind Jugnauth  cut the Indian Ocean island nation’s economic growth
forecast for 2010 to between 3.5 percent and 4 percent, citing
the euro crisis. Europe accounted for 61 percent of Mauritius’s
exports in the first quarter of this year, while two-thirds of
visitors to the island nation are from Europe, according to the
Central Statistics Office.  
 Honeywell Flour Mills Plc  (HONYFLOU NL), a Nigerian wheat
processor, advanced 15 kobo, or 1.8 percent, to 8.45 naira, the
strongest level in four weeks. The company expects profit for
the nine months through September of 661.1 million naira ($4.4
million), it said in a stock-exchange filing yesterday, without
providing a comparative figure.  
 Kenya Airways Ltd.  (KNAL KN), sub-Saharan Africa’s third-
largest airline, posted its biggest increase since June 2,
rising 1.6 percent to 46.75 shillings. The airline joined Air
France-KLM Group SA’s SkyTeam alliance, French daily Le Figaro
reported, citing Air France management.  
 Mauritius Commercial Bank  (MCB MP), the Indian Ocean island
nation’s largest company by market value, climbed to the highest
in more than four months, rising 2 rupees, 1.4 percent, to 141
rupees. The company will pay a final dividend of 3 rupees a
share, it said in as statement published after the market closed
on the Stock Exchange of Mauritius’s website yesterday.  
